I hope your college project about celebrating New Year in different countries is going well. Here are some ideas about New Year celebrations in China, where I grew up.

New Year in China is very important, and people often feel it's like a fresh start for the year. It's a time when many feel like they can reset things. One of the most interesting traditions is the lion dance. People dress up as a lion and perform a dance, often on TV shows that happen once a year, right at midnight when the New Year begins.

The TV show you watch is a big part of how people usually celebrate. There's a sort of unspoken schedule for the day. You wake up on New Year's Eve and start preparing for the celebrations. Then, when the clock strikes midnight, the excitement truly begins.

Everyone talks a lot, and all the lights are turned on. People who might be stressed with work often stop to watch the TV show. It's rare for anyone to sleep, except for young children. People catch up with each other, and you might see students who have done very well in their studies celebrating with their families. I really love this atmosphere.

I remember one year we visited our neighbours at 2 AM on New Year's Day, and they were still awake, celebrating with friends and family.

In China, New Year is more than just a tradition; it's a time that brings people together, filled with joy. I believe it's one of the most anticipated days in China.

Anyway, good luck with your college project!

